The '''Oran fatwa''' was a ''[[responsa|responsum]]'' [[fatwa]], or an Islamic legal opinion, issued in 1504 to address the crisis that occurred when [[Islam in Spain|Muslims]] in the [[Crown of Castile]] (in Spain) were [[Forced conversions of Muslims in Spain|forced to convert]] to Christianity in 1500{{ndash}}1502.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}} The fatwa sets out detailed relaxations of the [[sharia]] (Islamic law) requirements, allowing the Muslims to conform outwardly to Christianity and perform acts that are ordinarily forbidden in Islamic law, when necessary to survive.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266<!-- "It is particularly intriguing in that it grants comprehensive dispensation to Muslims living under the Inquisition to dissimulate{{snds}}to conform outwardly to Christianity in their daily lives, performing acts that are expressly forbidden in Islamic law, if necessary, just as long as they do this with the internal knowledge that these acts are ordinarily forbidden and without relinquishing their internal conviction."-->}} It includes relaxed instructions for fulfilling the [[salat|ritual prayers]], the [[zakat|ritual charity]], and the [[wudu|ritual ablution]], and recommendations when obliged to violate Islamic law, such as worshipping as Christians, committing [[Islam and blasphemy|blasphemy]], and consuming pork and wine.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=61–62}}

The fatwa enjoyed wide currency among Muslims and [[Morisco]]s (Muslims nominally converted to Christianity and their descendants) in [[History of Spain#Early Modern Spain|Spain]], and one of the surviving [[aljamiado]] translations was dated at 1564, 60{{nbsp}}years after the original fatwa.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} The fatwa has been described as the "key [[Kalam|theological]] document" to understand the practice of Spanish Muslims following the [[Reconquista]] up to the [[expulsion of the Moriscos]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}}{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}} The author of the fatwa (''mufti'') was [[Ahmad ibn Abi Jum'ah]], a North African scholar of Islamic law of the [[Maliki]] school.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=296}} The fatwa was termed the "[[Oran]] fatwa" by modern scholars, due to the word "Al-Wahrani" ("of Oran") that appears in the text as part of the author's name.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=273}}

The influence of the fatwa was limited to Spain.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} Outside the [[Iberian Peninsula]], the predominant opinion upheld the requirements of Islamic law and required Muslims to emigrate, or even choose [[martyrdom in Islam|martyrdom]], when the orthodox observance of the religion became impossible.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}}{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=152}}

== Background ==
{{see|Forced conversions of Muslims in Spain}}
Islam has been present in Spain since the [[Umayyad conquest of Hispania]] in the eighth century. At the beginning of the twelfth century, the Muslim population in the Iberian Peninsula&nbsp;— called "[[Al-Andalus]]" by the Muslims&nbsp;— was estimated to number up to 5.5&nbsp;million, among whom were [[Arabs]], [[Berbers]] and indigenous converts.{{sfn|Carr|2009|p=40}} In the next few centuries, as the Christians pushed from the north in a process called ''[[reconquista]]'', the Muslim population declined.{{sfn|Harvey|1992|p=9}} At the end of the fifteenth century, the ''reconquista'' culminated in the [[Granada War|fall of Granada]], and the total number of Muslims in Spain was estimated to be between 500,000 and 600,000 out of the total Spanish population of 7 to 8&nbsp;million.{{sfn|Carr|2009|p=40}} Approximately half of the Muslims lived in the former [[Emirate of Granada]], the last independent Muslim state in Spain, which had been annexed to the [[Crown of Castile]].{{sfn|Carr|2009|p=40}} About 20,000 Muslims lived in other territories of Castile, and most of the remainder lived in the territories of the [[Crown of Aragon]].{{sfn|Carr|2009|pp=40–41}}

[[File:The Moorish Proselytes of Archbishop Ximenes, Granada, 1500.jpg|thumb|Forced conversions to Christianity was the background of the fatwa. This 1873 painting depicts the mass baptism of Muslims in Granada by [[Francisco Jiménez de Cisneros|Cardinal Cisneros]].]]

Prior to the completion of the ''reconquista'', the defeated Muslims were generally given [[freedom of religion]] as terms of their surrender. For example, the [[Treaty of Granada]], which governed the surrender of the emirate, guaranteed a set of rights to the conquered Muslims, including religious tolerance and fair treatment, in return for their capitulation. The increasing occurrences of forced conversion triggered [[Rebellion of the Alpujarras (1499–1501)|a series of Muslim rebellions]] in Granada (1499–1501).{{sfn|Coleman|2003|p=6<!--quote=Outraged by Cisneros's efforts and his reported use of torture, Granada's Muslims in December 1499 rose up in an open rebellion that quickly spread to the nearby Alpujarras Mountains.-->}}{{sfn|Carr|2009|p=59}} The rebellions were suppressed, and afterwards the Muslims in Granada were no longer given the rights that had been provided to them by the Treaty of Granada.{{sfn|Lea|1901|p=35}} They were given the choice to remain and accept [[baptism]], to reject baptism and be enslaved or killed, or to be exiled.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=48}} The option of exile was often not feasible in practice because of the difficulty in uprooting one's family and making the journey to Muslim lands in North Africa, the inability to pay the fee required by the authorities for safe passage, and the general tendency by the authorities to discourage and hinder such an exodus.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=48}}

Some Muslims, especially those living near the [[Andalusia|southern coast]], took the option of exile,{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=48–49}} but for most, publicly converting to Christianity while secretly continuing to believe and practise Islam was the only available option for surviving as Muslims.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=49}} The population converted ''en masse'', and by 1501 the entire Muslim population of Granada was nominally converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Carr|2009|p=74}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=57}} The apparent success of Granada's forced conversions triggered a series of edicts and proclamations in 1501 and 1502 which effectively put the Muslims elsewhere in Castile to the same fate.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=57}} These new converts, along with their descendants, were known by Spanish sources as the [[Morisco]]s.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=6}} As well as having to accept Christianity and abandon the Islamic faith and rituals, they were also pressured to conform to Christian ways, including by attending church, sending their children to be instructed in the Christian doctrine, and partaking of food and beverages [[Islamic dietary laws|forbidden]] by Islamic law.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=49–52}}

=== Previous Islamic legal opinions ===
Prior to the Oran fatwa, the predominant position of Islamic scholars had been that a Muslim could not stay in a country where rulers made proper religious observance impossible.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=63–64}} Therefore, a Muslim's obligation was to leave, when they were able to do so.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} Even before the systematic forcible conversion, religious leaders had argued that Muslims in Christian territory would be subject to direct and indirect pressure, and preached emigration as a way to protect the religion from erosion.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=56}} Notably, the contemporary North African scholar [[Ahmad al-Wansharisi]], who was considered the leading authority on the subject of Muslims in Spain,{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=298}} wrote in 1491 that emigrating from Christian to Muslim lands was compulsory in almost all circumstances.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=56}} Further, Al-Wansharisi urged severe punishment for the Muslims who remained and predicted that they would temporarily dwell in [[Jahannam|hell in the afterlife]].{{sfn|Hendrickson|2009|p=25}}

== Authorship ==
The surviving translations of the fatwa give the name of the author in various slightly different forms. All of them are thought to be derived from the [[Arabic name]] Ahmad ibn Abi Jum'ah al-Maghrawi al-Wahrani, with some adding the name 'Ubaydallah, which might be a pious formula meaning "the little servant of God".{{sfn|Stewart|2007|pp=270–271}} The author's [[Nisba (onomastics)|nisba]]&nbsp;— the part of his name that indicates place of origin&nbsp;— ''al-Wahrani'' ("of Oran") refers to the city of [[Oran]] ({{lang-ar|وهران}},{{nbsp}}''Wahran'') in modern-day [[Algeria]], then part of the [[Zayyanid dynasty|Zayyanid]] [[kingdom of Tlemcen]].{{sfn|Dumper|Stanley|2008}} Thus, the author is often referred to as "the ''Mufti'' of Oran" and the document is called "the Oran fatwa", even though there appeared to be no indication that the fatwa was issued in Oran or that the author resided or had an official authority in Oran.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=273}} [[Devin J. Stewart|Devin Stewart]], an academic specialist in [[Islamic studies]], identified the author as [[Ahmad ibn Abi Jum'ah|Abu al-Abbas Ahmad ibn Abi Jum'ah al-Maghrawi al-Wahrani]] (b.{{nbsp}}unknown{{snds}}d.{{nbsp}}1511 in [[Fez]]), a [[Maliki]] jurist who had studied in Oran and [[Tlemcen]] and probably issued the fatwa in [[Fez, Morocco|Fez]] while a professor of Islamic law there.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=296}}

Al-Wahrani drafted the fatwa in response to a request of legal opinion, in other words, as a ''[[responsa|responsum]]'', to Muslim petitioners who wished to learn if they could continue to live in Christian Spain.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}}{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}}{{sfn|Garcia-Arenal|Rodríguez Mediano|2013|p=290}} The recipient of the fatwa is not named.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}} The commonly accepted date of the composition of the fatwa is 1{{nbsp}}[[Rajab]] 910{{nbsp}}AH, as this was the date that appears in most of the surviving manuscripts.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=270}} This day in the [[Islamic calendar]] corresponds to around 8{{nbsp}}December 1504.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=269}} One manuscript added "3{{nbsp}}May 1563" in addition to 1{{nbsp}}Rajab 910, which would have been a date conversion error, but both Stewart and the historian [[L.&nbsp;P.&nbsp;Harvey]] have suggested that the 1563 date might have been the time of the translation.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=269}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} One other manuscript gives "Rajab{{nbsp}}909", which was probably a copying error.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=270}}

== Content ==
The opening of the fatwa displayed sympathy to the Muslims of Spain, who kept their religious faith despite the suffering and risk that this posed them. The ''mufti'' (author of the fatwa) exhorted that they continue to adhere to the religion of Islam and instruct it to their children when the latter reached maturity.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}}

The fatwa reaffirmed the obligation of Spanish Muslims to perform the [[salat|ritual prayers]] (''salat''), the [[zakat|ritual charity]] (''zakat''), and the ritual ablution (''[[ghusl]]''), even if they could not be performed in the correct form.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} It described the obligation of the ritual prayers{{snds}}normally performed by standing, bowing, [[prostration|prostrating]], and sitting in a prescribed sequence{{snds}}even if done only by making slight movements.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} The fatwa also allowed the omission of the prayers{{snds}}normally performed an obligatory five times a day at prescribed times{{snds}}when they were prevented from doing so, and instructed them to make up the missed prayers at night instead.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} It also provided instructions for performing the [[tayammum|ritual dry ablution]] (''tayammum'') when ritually pure water was not available, to replace the [[wudu|ritual ablution]] (''wudu'') that is ordinarily required before performing the ''salat''.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} When ''tayammum'' was not possible, even making slight pointing motions with hands or face toward clean earth, stone, or tree was acceptable.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}}

The fatwa also maintained the Islamic obligation to give the ritual charity (''zakat''){{snds}}normally calculated and distributed in a specific manner prescribed by the [[sharia]] (Islamic law){{snds}}even if this could only be done by showing generosity to a beggar.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} It affirmed the obligation of the ritual ablution (''ghusl''), "even though by plunging into the sea".{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}}

The fatwa permitted Muslims outwardly to participate in Christian rituals and worship, so long as they inwardly considered them to be forbidden. When the Muslims had to prostrate to Christian "idols", they were to internally desire to perform the Islamic prayer, even if not actually [[Qibla|facing Mecca]], and when they bowed down to the "idols", they were to focus their attention toward [[God in Islam|Allah]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} When obliged to commit [[Islam and blasphemy|blasphemy]], such as cursing [[Muhammad]], or accepting [[Jesus]] as the [[God the Son|son of God]] or [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]] as [[Veneration of Mary in the Catholic Church|God's wife]] [''[[sic]]''], the fatwa instructed them to do so, and to employ "whatever stratagems" they could to negate their meaning whenever possible. For example, the fatwa suggested mispronouncing the name of Muhammad, or intending to curse someone else with a similar name, when being required to curse the prophet.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=62}}

The fatwa also allowed Spain's Muslims to consume [[alcohol in Islam|wine]], [[Religious restrictions on the consumption of pork|pork]], and other things normally forbidden by the sharia, as long as the Muslims did not intend to take advantage of them and rejected them in their hearts.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=61–62}}{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=177}} The fatwa reaffirmed the permissibility of a Muslim man [[Interfaith marriage in Islam|marrying a Christian woman]], under the reasoning that both Muslims and Christians were [[People of the Book]].{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=62}} Marriage between a Muslim woman and a Christian man was to be avoided unless under duress, and while doing so the Muslims should "cleave firmly to the belief that that is forbidden".{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=62}}

At the end of the fatwa, the author encouraged the Muslims to write to the ''mufti'' about anything else that presented difficulty to them, so that he could give further legal opinions. The fatwa discreetly did not name any specific recipient, and instead designated the persons it was addressed to by "''al-guraba''" (those living abroad) yet near to Allah".{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}}

== Reactions ==
=== Impact in Spain ===
[[File:La Expulsión en el Puerto de Denia. Vicente Mostre.jpg|thumb|The opinion in the fatwa had a lasting impact in the Morisco community until their [[Expulsion of the Moriscos|expulsion from Spain]] in 1609{{ndash}}1614, depicted in ''The Expulsion at the Port of [[Denia]]'' by Vicente Mostre, 1613.]]

The fatwa appeared to enjoy wide currency within the Muslim and Morisco community in various kingdoms of Spain, for it was translated and copied as late as 1563 and 1609.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} The full geographical reach of the text is unknown, but it appeared to be originally addressed to the Muslims (or Moriscos) of Castile as a response to their forced conversions in 1500–1502.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} After the forced conversion was extended to the Crown of Aragon in the 1520s, the fatwa likely circulated there, too.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}}

The opinion formed the basis of the Moriscos' Islamic status and practices for more than a century, until [[Expulsion of the Moriscos|their expulsion]] in 1609–1614.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} This led to a non-traditional form of Islam, in which one's internal intention (''[[niyya]]''), rather than external observation of rituals and laws, was the defining characteristic of one's Islam.{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=153}} Generations of Moriscos were born and died within this religious climate.{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=153}} Hybrid or undefined religious practice featured in many Morisco texts.{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|pp=153–154}} For example, the works of the Morisco writer known as "the [[Young Man of Arévalo]]", written c.{{nbsp}}1530s described [[crypto-Muslim]]s using Christian worship as replacement for regular Islamic rituals, as recommended in the fatwa.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=185}}

The influence of the fatwa was limited to Spain.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} Outside the Iberian Peninsula, the predominant opinion continued to uphold the unbending requirements of Islamic law and required Muslims to leave any country, or even choose [[martyrdom in Islam|martyrdom]], where approved observance of the religion became impossible.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}}{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=152}}

=== Scholarly analysis ===
Modern scholars of Spanish Islamic history stressed the historical importance of the fatwa. Harvey called it "the key theological document" for the study of Spanish Islam following the forced conversions, a description which Stewart repeated.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}}{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}} Mercedes García-Arenal and Fernando Rodríguez Mediano, historians of Spain and Western Muslims, described the fatwa as "famous" and called it "one of the most important theological texts of later Spanish Islam".{{sfn|Garcia-Arenal|Rodríguez Mediano|2013|p=290}} Spanish literature scholar María del Mar Rosa-Rodríguez considered the fatwa important because it officially documented "the existence of religiosities that do not depend on traditional ritual practice".{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=157}}

Harvey and Stewart said that the fatwa was a departure from the previous legal opinions among Islamic scholars, which typically emphasised the obligation to emigrate from any country where proper religious observance was not possible.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=63–64}}{{sfn|Stewart|2007|pp=266, 298–299}} Notably, the Maliki scholar [[al-Wansharisi]], the leading living authority on the issue, was among the proponents of this view.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=299}} Stewart contended that, while the fatwa's text did not mention any opponent, it was intended as a rebuke against the views of al-Wansharisi.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=299}} Recipients of this fatwa would be able to stay put, outwardly conforming to Christianity and not see themselves as abandoning their faith.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} The fatwa addressed the recipient as "''al-guraba''", a word that means "outsiders" or "those living abroad", but this word also appears in several [[hadith]]s (sayings of [[Muhammad]]) and evokes a spiritual meaning of heroic Muslims loyal to their faith in spite of great suffering.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}}{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=63}} The sympathy shown by the author, as well as his acknowledgement of the Muslims' loyalty and suffering, is in contrast with the predominant opinion such as al-Wansharisi's which saw them unfavourably.{{sfn|Hendrickson|2009|p=25}}

Harvey did not consider the fatwa as a permanent and universal relaxation of the sharia; instead, the sender and the recipients of the fatwa must have seen its provisions as temporary expedients under extraordinary circumstances intended to help the Muslims of Spain through the crisis.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=64}} The fatwa began by affirming in orthodox terms the obligations of all Muslims,{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=61}} and ended by expressing hopes that Islam may again be practised openly without ordeals, tribulations and fear.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=63}} The ''mufti'' and many Moriscos expected or hoped that the crisis to end at some not-too-distant time.{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=152}} Rosa-Rodriguez noted that the fatwa stated a hope that the "Noble Turks" would soon intervene and end the religious persecution in Spain, a reference to the [[Ottoman Empire]]'s growing power in the Mediterranean at the time.{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=151–152}} This hope did not materialise, and the religious persecution in Spain continued, causing the fatwa's recommendations to become the normal way of practicing Islam for generations.{{sfn|Rosa-Rodríguez|2010|p=152}}

Harvey also noted that the fatwa covered a wide range of Islamic religious duties, while usually a ''responsum'' fatwa only addresses a specific enquiry on a difficult point of detail.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=60}} The fatwa also went into specific practical challenges faced by Muslims in Spain, such as the pressure to curse Muhammad, eat pork, drink wine, and intermarry with the Christians. This suggests that the author had some knowledge of what life under Christian rule was like.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|p=65}}

=== In popular culture ===
[[Amin Maalouf]]'s 1986 novel ''[[Leo Africanus (novel)|Leo Africanus]]'' features a fictionalised version of the fatwa. In the novel, Muslim exiles from Granada and the local [[ulama]] (Islamic scholars) held meetings in Fez to provide counsel to the Muslims in Granada, who sent letters describing their persecution and their dilemma. Amid the meetings, the protagonist of the novel witnessed the "man from Oran" delivering a speech similar in content to the Oran fatwa.{{sfn|Maalouf|1998|pp=115–116}}

== Surviving manuscripts ==
[[File:Sistinehall.jpg|thumb|The Vatican Library, which houses the only surviving Arabic copy of the fatwa]]

As of 2006, there are four known surviving manuscripts containing the fatwa. One of them is an Arabic copy, discovered by [[Muhammad Abdullah 'Inan]] in [[Vatican City|the Vatican]] in 1951 and kept in the Borgiano collection of the [[Vatican Library]].{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}} The other three were translations to [[aljamiado|Spanish written in the Arabic script]] (''aljamiado''). One of them was kept in [[Aix-en-Provence]], [[France]], and one in [[Madrid]], Spain.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|pp=266–267}} The third ''aljamiado'' translation used to be in Madrid, but its location is currently unknown.{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=267}}{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=300}}

Since the discovery, the texts have been transcribed or translated into modern [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[English language|English]] and [[German language|German]].{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=266}} Historian L.&nbsp;P.&nbsp;Harvey provides a near-complete English translation in his book ''Muslims in Spain, 1500 to 1615''.{{sfn|Harvey|2005|pp=61–63}}{{sfn|Stewart|2007|p=267}}

